# Hong Kong VAR Model — Auto-Run Rules

## After any edit to the model

When `hk_var_model.py` is modified, run:

```bash
cd "/Users/stevenchung/Desktop/P12B_File/Hong Kong"
MPLCONFIGDIR=/tmp/mpl_cfg python hk_var_model.py --lag-criterion bic --model-type var
```

Use `--lag-criterion bic` (stable, 3 lags). AIC selects 8 lags which overparameterizes the system.

## After any edit to tests

When `tests/test_hk_var_model.py` or `hk_var_model.py` is modified, run:

```bash
cd "/Users/stevenchung/Desktop/P12B_File/Hong Kong"
MPLCONFIGDIR=/tmp/mpl_cfg python -m pytest tests/test_hk_var_model.py -v --tb=short
```

All 59+ tests must pass. Fix any failures before proceeding.

## After any edit to the paper

When any `.tex` or `.bib` file in `paper/` is modified, recompile:

```bash
cd "/Users/stevenchung/Desktop/P12B_File/Hong Kong/paper"
pdflatex -interaction=nonstopmode main.tex && bibtex main && pdflatex -interaction=nonstopmode main.tex && pdflatex -interaction=nonstopmode main.tex
```

## Key project facts

- **Research question**: How do US monetary policy shocks and China growth shocks propagate to HK under the currency board?
- **Data**: 107 quarters (1998Q1–2024Q3), 6 variables, real data from FRED + World Bank in `data/hk_macro_quarterly_real.csv`
- **Cholesky ordering**: external-first `[us_ffr, china_gdp, gdp_growth, cpi_inflation, unemployment, hibor_3m]`
- **Headline finding**: China drives ~78% of HK GDP variance; US FFR drives ~59% of HIBOR variance
- **Outputs**: All charts/tables go to `output/`, paper in `paper/`
- **MPLCONFIGDIR=/tmp/mpl_cfg** must prefix all python commands to avoid matplotlib cache warnings
